{
  "text": "Sinusoidal obstruction syndrome (SOS) is a rare vascular disease of the liver, which can lead to lethal liver failure and portal-hypertension-related complications [CITATION_1] . The clinical syndrome is characterized [CITATION_2] by hepatomegaly, ascites, weight gain, increased aminotransferase levels, and jaundice due to sinusoidal congestion, which can be caused by alkaloid ingestion [CITATION_3] , hematopoietic stem cell transplantation (HSCT) [CITATION_4] , bone marrow transplantation, and radiationinduced liver disease or chemotherapy, and it is also seen after solid organ transplantation [CITATION_5] . The most common cause of SOS in China is herbal medicines containing pyrrolizidine alkaloids, mostly Tusanqi (Gynura segetum) [CITATION_6] .",
